India Equity Movers: Cairn, Gujarat Gas, Madhucon, Ranbaxy

-- B y   A m e y a   K a r v e
-- 
2011-03-21T10:57:57Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-21/india-equity-movers-ashok-leyland-cairn-pipavav-voltas.html
The following companies had unusual
price changes in India trading. Stock symbols are in parentheses
and share prices are as of the 3:30 p.m. close in Mumbai.  The Bombay Stock Exchange Sensitive Index, or Sensex, fell
39.76, or 0.2 percent, to 17,839.05, for a third straight
trading day.    Cairn India Ltd. (CAIR)  , operator of the nation’s
biggest onshore oil field, increased 1 percent to 349.35 rupees,
its highest closing price since March 8. The  Securities and
Exchange Board of India  approved Vedanta Resources Plc’s open
offer for Cairn India shares, ET Now news channel reported on
March 18, without saying where it got the information.  Gujarat Gas Co. (GGAS IN) fell 3.7 percent to 374 rupees,
its steepest decline since Feb. 1. The unit of U.K.’s BG Group
Plc that operates in the western Indian state of Gujarat began
trading today without the right to receive a payout of 8 rupees
a share in addition to a dividend of 4 rupees apiece.    Madhucon Projects Ltd. (MDHPJ)   surged 4.6 percent to
91.55 rupees, its highest advance since Feb. 17. The engineering
and construction company won a contract valued at 15 billion
rupees from the National Highways Authority of India in the
eastern state of Jharkhand.    Ranbaxy Laboratories Ltd. (RBXY)   plunged 7 percent to
436.05 rupees, the most since May 2009. Mylan Inc. sued the U.S.  Food and Drug Administration  seeking to block Ranbaxy’s
exclusive rights to sell a generic version of Pfizer Inc.’s
cholesterol pill Lipitor.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Ameya Karve in Mumbai at 
 akarve@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Darren Boey at 
 dboey@bloomberg.net  